The Pandas API on Spark, found at pyspark dot pandas, lets you write familiar pandas code that runs on a distributed Spark cluster. Instead of learning an entirely new API, you import pyspark dot pandas as ps and use the same DataFrame and Series interfaces you already know — but backed by Spark's execution engine.

In a banking context this matters when a pandas workflow that worked fine on a sample of one hundred thousand transactions breaks down on five hundred million rows. The Pandas API on Spark scales the same code without a full rewrite.

The Three DataFrame APIs.

It helps to see the three APIs side by side. The standard pandas library runs on a single machine, evaluates eagerly, and guarantees row ordering. The native Spark DataFrame API runs on a distributed cluster, evaluates lazily, and does not guarantee row order — but gives you full control and the best performance. The Pandas API on Spark sits in between: it runs on a distributed cluster and evaluates lazily, but exposes a pandas-style interface. Under the hood, every pyspark dot pandas call is translated into a Spark logical plan and executed by Spark.

Creating Pandas-on-Spark DataFrames.

There are three common ways to create a pyspark dot pandas DataFrame.

The first is from a plain pandas DataFrame. You call ps dot from pandas and pass the pandas DataFrame. The result looks and behaves like a pandas DataFrame but runs on Spark.

The second is from a Spark DataFrame. You call dot to underscore pandas underscore on underscore spark on any existing Spark DataFrame. This is the idiomatic bridge when you already have data loaded in Spark.

The third is directly from Python data, using ps dot DataFrame with a dictionary — identical to the pd dot DataFrame syntax you already know.

Common Operations.

Column selection, boolean filtering, and descriptive statistics all use the same syntax as pandas. You pass a list of column names to select columns. You use bracket notation with a boolean condition to filter rows. You call dot describe to get summary statistics — but remember that each of these triggers a distributed Spark job on the full dataset, not just a local computation.

Value counts work the same way: call dot value underscore counts on a Series to get a frequency table. Internally this becomes a groupBy and count in Spark.

GroupBy and Aggregation.

GroupBy syntax is identical to pandas. You chain dot groupby, a column selection, and dot agg with a list of aggregation names such as count, sum, and mean. Dot reset underscore index promotes the group key back to a regular column, just as in pandas.

The transform method is also supported — it lets you broadcast a group-level statistic back to each row. For example, dividing each transaction amount by the group total gives each row its percentage share of the status group.

Merge.

ps dot merge supports the same join types as pd dot merge: inner, left, right, and outer. You pass the two DataFrames, the key column with the on parameter, and the join type with the how parameter. Internally this becomes a Spark join.

Converting Between APIs.

Moving data between pandas, pandas-on-Spark, and native Spark DataFrames is explicit and uses a small set of methods you should memorise.

To go from a plain pandas DataFrame to a Spark DataFrame, use spark dot createDataFrame and pass the pandas DataFrame. Spark infers the schema from the pandas dtypes.

To go from a plain pandas DataFrame to a pandas-on-Spark DataFrame, use ps dot from pandas.

To go from a pandas-on-Spark DataFrame to a native Spark DataFrame, call dot to underscore spark. This gives you a pyspark dot sql dot DataFrame — useful when you need a Spark SQL function that pyspark dot pandas does not expose.

To go from a pandas-on-Spark DataFrame to a plain pandas DataFrame, call dot to underscore pandas. This collects all the data to the driver, so only do this for small results.

To go from a Spark DataFrame to plain pandas, call dot to pandas or dot toPandas — both collect to driver.

Index Behaviour and the Default Index Type Setting.

Pandas guarantees a meaningful integer index. Distributed DataFrames do not — rows live across partitions with no natural global order. pyspark dot pandas offers three index strategies.

The sequence strategy assigns zero, one, two in order. This requires a full sort across the cluster and is expensive.

The distributed dash sequence strategy assigns consecutive integers computed per partition in parallel. Cheaper than sequence but still requires one pass over the data.

The distributed strategy assigns non-consecutive partition-local identifiers at zero extra cost. This is the recommended setting.

You set it globally with ps dot set underscore option, the key "compute dot default underscore index underscore type", and the value "distributed". You can also pin a natural key as the index when converting from Spark by passing the index underscore col parameter to to underscore pandas underscore on underscore spark.

Execution Model.

Every pyspark dot pandas operation is translated into a Spark logical plan and executed lazily. A Spark job fires only when you call an action — head, to underscore pandas, count, or any aggregation that returns a scalar. Chaining transformations is free. Only the final action triggers computation.

When to Use Each API.

Use standard pandas when the data fits in memory on one machine — it has the full feature set and no Spark overhead.

Use the native pyspark dot sql API for new Spark code where performance is the priority — full control over the execution plan and best throughput.

Use pyspark dot pandas when you are migrating an existing pandas pipeline to Spark scale and want to minimise code changes.

Use a pandas underscore U D F, covered in notebook eleven, when you need vectorised row-wise transformations inside a native Spark DataFrame pipeline.

On Databricks, pyspark dot pandas is the official replacement for the legacy Koalas package. The import and behaviour are the same.

Limitations.

Not every pandas operation is supported or behaves identically in pyspark dot pandas, and it is important to know the key restrictions for the exam.

Row order is not guaranteed. Sort values produces a correct sort, but the index is not stable across runs unless you pin a natural key with index underscore col.

The inplace equals True parameter is not supported. Always assign the result to a new variable.

Iterrows and itertuples are not supported. They collect to the driver and defeat the purpose of distributed processing.

Row-wise apply, that is apply with axis equals one, works but is slow. Internally each row is serialised to Python. Prefer column-wise apply or rewrite using a pandas U D F.

Multi-index support is limited. Prefer flat indexes.

When you hit an unsupported operation, the recommended pattern is to convert to a native Spark DataFrame, apply the Spark SQL function, and convert back.

Summary.

Import pyspark dot pandas as ps to get a pandas-compatible API backed by Spark — scale without a full rewrite.

Create ps dot DataFrame from plain pandas using ps dot from underscore pandas, from a Spark DataFrame using dot to underscore pandas underscore on underscore spark, or directly from Python data.

Convert back with dot to underscore spark for a native Spark DataFrame, or dot to underscore pandas to collect to plain pandas on the driver.

Use spark dot createDataFrame to go from a plain pandas DataFrame straight to a native Spark DataFrame.

Set the default index type to distributed to avoid expensive global sorting.

Operations are lazy — only actions trigger a Spark job.

Avoid inplace equals True, iterrows, and row-wise apply — use native Spark functions or a pandas U D F instead.

On Databricks, pyspark dot pandas replaces the legacy Koalas library.
